📄 Part 4 – Incoming Flow, Acknowledgement Handling, Retry Mechanism and Closure Logic


---

1. Introduction

After the Track & Trace data is sent from Conserto to Connexis, the system must handle the response returned by Connexis. This response determines whether the transaction was successfully processed or failed.

This section explains:

How incoming data from Connexis is processed

How ACK and NACK responses are handled

How retry logic works

How the system ensures proper closure of transactions



---

2. Incoming Response Overview

Once a TAR file is sent to Connexis, the external system processes the request and sends back a response.

Response Format

The response is received as a TAR file

The TAR file contains an XML file



---

Purpose of the Response

The response indicates:

Whether the request was successfully processed (ACK)

Whether the request failed (NACK)

Additional error details (if any)



---

3. Incoming Processing Flow

The system follows a structured approach to process incoming responses.


---

Step 1: File Reception

The system receives a TAR file from Connexis



---

Step 2: File Extraction

The TAR file is uncompressed

XML file is extracted



---

Step 3: XML Parsing

The XML file is parsed

Relevant fields are extracted



---

Step 4: Event Identification

The system identifies the corresponding event using:

<additional_field name="mo_event_id" type="string" scope="transaction">


---

Explanation

This field contains the actual Event ID from Conserto

It is used to match the response with the correct record in DPW_EVENT



---

Step 5: Database Lookup

Using the Event ID, the system finds the corresponding event in the database



---

Step 6: Data Update

The system updates:

Connexis Reference ID

Connexis Transaction ID

Connexis Status




---

4. Key Fields Extracted from XML

Field	Description

ref_id	Connexis reference ID
tnx_id	Connexis transaction ID
ack_status	Indicates success or failure
comment_error_message	Error message from Connexis
cxt_client_ref	Client reference (optional)



---

5. ACK and NACK Handling (Critical Logic)


---

Definition

Value	Meaning

01	ACK (Successful processing)
02	NACK (Failed processing)



---

Correct Handling (After Fix)

The system correctly maps:

XML Value	Database Status

01	ACK
02	NACK



---

Previous Issue (Resolved in Build 5)

Earlier:

ack_status = 02 was incorrectly stored as MESSAGE_PUBLISHED


This caused:

Incorrect status tracking

No retry for failed transactions



---

Fix Applied

Proper mapping implemented

NACK is now correctly stored



---

Impact

Accurate status tracking

Correct retry behavior

Improved reliability



---

6. Error Handling


---

Error Source

Errors can come from:

Invalid XML structure

Missing mandatory fields

Business validation failure in Connexis



---

Handling Mechanism

Error message is extracted from:


<additional_field name="comment_error_message">

Stored in logs

Linked with the event



---

Purpose

Helps in debugging

Allows users to understand failure reasons



---

